3. Create a Scatter Plot using ggplot2

Scatter plots are useful for visualizing the relationship between two quantitative variables (numerical values which represents some kind of measurements such as number of students, height, weight, etc). Let’s exploring the relationship between the carat and price variables in the diamonds dataset.

To achieve this, we’ll be using ggplot2, a powerful R package for data visualization that’s built on the principles of “The Grammar of Graphics.” The core idea is to start with a blank canvas and then iteratively add layers to it. These layers can include aesthetic mappings, which define how variables in your dataset are mapped to visual properties (cues), as well as geometric features that dictate the shape and structure of the visualizations.

  • “gg”: Grammar of Graphics.
  • aesthetic: mapping between a visual cue and variable.

3.1 Blank Canvas

First, start with a blank canvas

ggplot()

3.2 Aesthetic mapping

Second, add a layer of geometric features to the blank canvas via “aesthetic mapping”. Specify values through “aes()”

ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(x=carat,y=price),data=diamonds)

3.3 Color mapping

ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(x=carat,y=price),data=diamonds,color="red")

ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(x=carat,y=price,color="blue"),data=diamonds)

## what's wrong with the plot?

You can map (inside aes) a variable of your data to an aesthetic, e.g. (aes(color=cut)) or you can set (outside aes, but inside a geom element) an aesthetic to a constant value, e.g. “blue”

ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(x=carat,y=price,color=cut),data=diamonds)

3.4 Self Defined Colors

If you don’t like the default color, you can also specify it. scale_color_manual() can be used for lines and points.

ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(x=carat,y=price,color=cut),data=diamonds)+
  scale_color_manual(values=c("red","orange","yellow","green","blue"))

3.5 Other Color Schemes

  • RGB triplet - combinations of different amounts of red, green, and blue (e.g., Red:255, Green:0, Blue:0 represents the color Red)
  • Hexadecimal format (e.g., Red:FF, Green:00, Blue:00 or #FF0000)
  • #000000 : Black
  • #FFFFFF : White
  • Ref: http://www.fifi.org/doc/wwwcount/Count2.5/rgb.txt.html
  • 1- viridis: printer-friendly, uniform and easy to read by those with colorblindness - scale_color_viridis() and scale_fill_viridis()
  • 2- RColorBrewer: contains 3 types of color palettes: sequential, diverging, and qualitative - scale_color_brewer() and scale_fill_brewer()
  • 3- Grey color pallet: scale_color_grey() and scale_fill_grey()
  • Ref: https://www.datanovia.com/en/blog/top-r-color-palettes-to-know-for-great-data-visualization/
ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(x=carat,y=price,color=cut),data=diamonds)+
  scale_color_viridis_d() # d stands for discrete

# scale_color_viridis_d() : discrete data
# scale_color_viridis_c() : continuous data
# scale_color_viridis_b() : bin continuous data

# viridis color palettes
# 1. printer-friendly
# 2. perceptually uniform; a change of the same amount in a color value should produce a change of about the same visual importance
# 3. colorblind-friendly

Refer for this for more details about the colors https://www.datanovia.com/en/blog/ggplot-colors-best-tricks-you-will-love/

3.6 Colorblind-friendly Color Schemes.

  • About 1 in 12 men (8%) and 1 in 200 women in the world are color blind.
  • https://www.nceas.ucsb.edu/sites/default/files/2022-06/Colorblind%20Safe%20Color%20Schemes.pdf
  • https://r-graphics.org/recipe-colors-palette-discrete-colorblind
  • R package colorBlindness: https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/colorBlindness/vignettes/colorBlindness.html#Safe_colorsets
  • http://www.cookbook-r.com/Graphs/Colors_(ggplot2)/#a-colorblind-friendly-palette
ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(x=carat,y=price,color=cut),data=diamonds) +
  scale_color_manual(values=c("#999999", "#E69F00", "#56B4E9", "#009E73","#F0E442"))

3.7 Problem: Overplotting

ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(x=carat,y=price),data=diamonds)

# Any problems?

3.7.1 Solution: Use geom_count() or geom_hex()

Can summarize the number of points at each location and display that in some way, using geom_count() or geom_hex()

  • geom_count: a variant geom_point() that counts the number of observations at each location, then maps the count to point area. It useful when you have discrete data and overplotting (https://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/reference/geom_count.html)
  • geom_hex(): Divides the plane into regular hexagons, counts the number of cases in each hexagon, and then (by default) maps the number of cases to the hexagon fill (https://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/reference/geom_hex.html)
ggplot() +
  geom_count(aes(x=carat,y=price),data=diamonds)

ggplot() +
  # bins: numeric vector giving number of bins in both vertical and horizontal directions. Set to 30 by default.
  geom_hex(aes(x=carat,y=price),data=diamonds, bins=50)

3.7.2 Add alpha blending

# Reduce the alpha level to make each point semi-transparent 
ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(x=carat,y=price),data=diamonds,alpha=0.3)

3.8 Add Labels

Adding labels for the axes can also be regarded as a layer

ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(x=carat,y=price),data=diamonds,alpha=0.3) +
  labs(x="Carat",y="Price in US Dollars") # title also can be added here

3.9 Add Titles

ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(x=carat, y=price,color=clarity), 
             data=diamonds) +
  labs(x="Carat", y="Price in US Dollars") +
  # title using ggtitle() Or inside labs(title = ) : labs(x="Carat", y="Price in US Dollars", title = "The Scatter Plot of Price (US$) and Carat") +
  ggtitle("The Scatter Plot of Price (US$) and Carat")

3.10 Change size/shape of point

  • Aesthetic specifications:
  • http://www.sthda.com/english/wiki/ggplot2-point-shapes
  • https://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/articles/ggplot2-specs.html
ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(x=carat, y=price,color=cut),
             size=3,shape=3,data=diamonds) +
  labs(x="Carat", y="Price in US Dollars")+
  ggtitle("The Scatter Plot of Price (US$) and Carat Colored by Cut")+
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") #top, left, right

#size - (default: 0.5) diameter of the point
#shape - (default: 16=dot) the shape of the point

3.11 Legends

Let’s change name of the legend

ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(x=carat, y=price,color=cut),
             size=3,shape=3,data=diamonds) +
  # For changing legend title we also can use guides() and guide_legend() functions: guides(colour=guide_legend(title = "Diamonds Cut")) 
  # We will explore the details of the guieds() function later
  labs(x="Carat", y="Price in US Dollars",color="Diamonds Cut")+
  ggtitle("The Scatter Plot of Price (US$) and Carat Colored by Cut")+
  theme(legend.position = "right")

3.12 Display Layout panels in a grid

  • https://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/reference/facet_grid.html
  • Syntax: facet_grid(var_vertical ~ var_horizontal)
  • Create a matrix of panels defined by row and column faceting variables. It is most useful when you have two discrete variables, and all combinations of the variables exist in the data. If you have only one variable with many levels, try facet_wrap()

3.12.1 Vertical direction

ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(x=carat, y=price,color=cut),
             size=3,alpha=0.5,data=diamonds) +
  labs(x="Carat", y="Price in US Dollars",color="Diamonds Cut")+
  ggtitle("The Scatter Plot of Price (US$) and Carat Colored by Cut")+
  theme(legend.position = "right")+
  facet_grid(cut~.)

3.12.2 Horizontal direction

p1 <- ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(x=carat, y=price,color=cut),
             size=2,shape=2,data=diamonds) +
  labs(x="Carat", y="Price in US Dollars",color="Diamonds Cut")+
  ggtitle("The Scatter Plot of Price (US$) and Carat Colored by Cut")+
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")

p1+facet_grid(.~cut)

3.13 Complete themes

  • https://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/reference/ggtheme.html
p1 + 
  facet_grid(.~cut) +
  theme_minimal()

  #theme_classic() - theme_gray() - theme_bw() - theme_light() - theme_void ()
